    <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
      <head>Biographical History</head>
      <p>Edward J. Mowery (1906-1970) was an American journalist, awarded the Pulitzer Prize in 1953 "for his reporting of 
	  the facts which brought vindication and freedom to Louis Hoffner," falsely convicted of murder.</p>
	  
	  <p>Edward J. Mowery was born in Lancaster, Ohio on March 8, 1906.  He attended Ohio State University and Notre Dame between 
	  1924 and 1929,  During his journalism career he served as feature writer and editor for many newspapers, including the 
	  Columbus Citizen, the Lancaster Daily Eagle, the New York Post, the New York World-Telegram, and the New York Herald Tribune.  
	  Starting in 1966 Mowery wrote a syndicated column, "Inside View," for General Features Syndicate.</p>
	  
	  <p>Mowery received many journalism awards including two NBC "Big Story" awards (1947, 1953) and the 1953 Pulitzer Prize for 
	  Journalism.  He also wrote two books, HUAC and the FBI: Targets for Abolition and Taxpayer's Governor.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
      <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
      <p>The <emph render="bold">Edward J. Mowery Papers</emph> consist of news clippings, news releases, writings and printed matter from Mowery's career in 
	  journalism.</p>
    </scopecontent>
    <arrangement encodinganalog="351$a">
      <head>Arrangement of the Collection</head>
      <p>Clippings are arranged chronologically.  Other material is arranged alphabetically.</p>
    </arrangement>
